<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7566> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7566" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "See MRR 2.287. Sumner accepts his quaestorship, in either 47 or 46 (Phoenix 25, 1971, 263-264), and from his praenomen suggests that he was a third son of the consul of 64. Cf. below, on Cn. Iuli(us) L. f. (Caesar?).\n" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7066> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7066" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Q(uaestor), named on quadrantes of Corduba. In MRR 2.287, he is dated, at Grant's suggestion, to 47 or 46. In Moneda hispanica en la Edad Antigua (Madrid, 1966), 300-301, no. 1263, Gil Farres agrees that the head of Venus on the obverse and the Cupid with torch and cornucopia refer to the Iulian gens, but puts the date, though still uncertain, before 49. See C. Castillo, Hispania Antigua 4, 1974, 191-202; R. C. Knapp, Aspects 187. But in Roman Cordoba 15-16, although Knapp admits that Cn. Iulius may be a Roman official, and as a L(uci) f(ilius) possibly connected with the family of the consul of 64, he thinks that a date of 120-100 for the coins is preferable, and, noting the praenomen Cn. is otherwise unknown in the Iulian gens in Italy, would consider this Cn. Iulius to be an obscure local quaestor, and perhaps an official of the Conventus civium Romanorum of Corduba. See below, on Cn. or C. Iulius Mento (360).\n" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5736> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5736" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Named as a Q(uaestor) on a coin of Corduba. Grant dates it in 47 or 46, and suggests that Iulius served under C. Trebonius or Q. Fabius Maximus (From Imperium to Auctoritas 4f.; see Mommsen, RMW 375, note 28)." .
